## PRIOR FINDINGS (build on these; do NOT duplicate; you MUST surface >=1 that these missed)
- F-3-1 [playbooks/P1] New-router cases belong in the seven compiled-eligible hub root playbooks plus system-skill-advisor, while child-mode playbooks remain out of scope.
- F-3-2 [playbooks/P0] The minimal canonical state corpus is four scenarios covering flag-off, flag-on fresh, drift-to-legacy, and causal seven-hub serving status.
- F-3-3 [unnamed/P0] The prompt-time hook cannot machine-enforce compiled routing because its recommendation type and rendered brief discard compiledRoute.
- F-3-4 [sk-code-align/P0] The public compiled front door supplies only prompt text, but sk-code surfaceBundle routing requires risk-slice and certificate context, so code-opencode cannot be proven end-to-end through the current interface.
- F-3-5 [playbooks/P1] The sk-doc root playbook still validates the retired flat RESOURCE_MAP router rather than the live eleven-packet hub contract.
- F-3-6 [activation/P0] The current legacy sentinel collapses flag-disabled, missing or malformed manifest, legacy authority, and engine failure, so a serving-status playbook cannot classify cause.
- F-3-7 [playbooks/P1] Prior LUNA route runs repeatedly exhausted the 150-second ceiling, so model timeout must be separated from routing correctness.
- F-3-8 [sk-code-align/P0] The named verify_alignment_drift.py gate checks language files but does not inspect the Markdown RESOURCE_MAP whose parent-child equality it is expected to enforce.
- F-4-1 [archiving/P0] The storage contract permits only a report JSON, its rendered Markdown, and an optional README, so compiled-vs-legacy parity must be embedded in the canonical Lane C report pair rather than archived as a copied spec-tree artifact.
- F-4-2 [archiving/P0] The existing baseline label is the frozen legacy pre-optimization anchor and must not be repurposed as the compiled-parity baseline.
- F-4-3 [activation/P0] The runtime resolves serving state from 010-live-activation while 006-parent-hub-rollout contains candidate manifests with different authority, so archiving the candidate tree can record non-serving evidence.
- F-4-4 [archiving/P1] Lane C live reports currently omit the exact model and variant even though the executor selects them, so a live-gpt-5-6-luna-high folder alone cannot prove the required LUNA HIGH subject.
- F-4-5 [unnamed/P1] Durable benchmark reports serialize an absolute worktree root, making archived evidence dependent on the originating machine and worktree path.
- F-5-1 [unnamed/P0] The advisor launcher strips SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING before spawning the daemon, so a parent-profile canary cannot activate the live advisor path.
- F-5-2 [activation/P0] Both current enablement predicates are fleet-global, so the specified hub-by-hub P4 cannot be performed by flipping those predicates literally.
- F-5-3 [activation/P0] All seven activation manifests are already compiled-serving, so making an unset flag mean enabled would activate the entire fleet simultaneously.
- F-5-4 [activation/P1] The existing routing drift workflow does not trigger on activation manifests, compiled runtime files, hub directives, or the advisor launcher.
- F-5-5 [unnamed/P0] HUB_CHILD is not merely a duplicated eligibility allowlist; it is also the runtime engine-location map, so removing it via manifest eligibility alone would break engine loading.
- F-5-6 [activation/P1] The ENV reference needs daemon-propagation and restart semantics in addition to flag polarity because advisor flags only work when forwarded to the resident child.
- F-5-7 [activation/P1] Each hub directive still encodes exact =1 opt-in semantics and therefore must change in the same commit as that hub enters the default-on cohort.
- F-6-1 [sk-code-align/P0] The named verifier `verify_alignment_drift.py` is explicitly markdown-blind (support only TS/JS/Python/Shell/Rust/JSON/JSONC; doc line 50-52 says 'does not scan markdown prose'), yet code-opencode/SKILL.md:51 implicitly cites it via 'a drift guard enforces that equality' — the actual guard is `sk-code-router-sync.vitest.ts:119-192`, two scripts away and not cross-referenced from the opencode surface.
- F-6-2 [sk-code-align/P0] The compiled-router emits `targetQualifiedIds` (e.g. `sk-code/code-review/code-review/workflow/review-cache`) while the code-opencode surface RESOURCE_MAP emits surface-relative paths (e.g. `references/shared/hooks.md`) — no typed-pair contract bridges the two vocabularies, so 015's Phase 3 typed-gold derivation cannot cover the compiled-vs-surface parity it implicitly needs.
- F-6-3 [unnamed/P1] Two duplicated allowlists for the same 7 compiled-serving hubs (`advisor-recommend.ts:41-49` COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS Set vs spec-tree `compiled-route.cjs:23-31` HUB_CHILD map) have no cross-check; an 8th hub added to one but not the other causes the advisor to attach a `compiledRoute` field the resolver cannot compute, or vice versa.
- F-6-4 [sk-code-align/P2] `hub-router.json:32-36` declares code-opencode with a single resource `code-opencode/SKILL.md`, so when router-replay loads the hub router directly (e.g. for a non-OPENCODE-detected task that scores code-opencode intent), it returns only the SKILL.md pointer — bypassing the per-intent RESOURCE_MAP union that the parent surface router would have assembled via `loadSurfaceRouter`. The hub-router level is therefore lossy by design.
- F-6-5 [sk-code-align/P1] Three disjoint drift guards (`verify_alignment_drift.py` code-files, `verify_stack_folders.py` language folders, `sk-code-router-sync.vitest.ts` Markdown RESOURCE_MAP) cover code-opencode with zero overlap and no orchestrating contract; a regression in any layer is caught only by the matching guard, and the named 'alignment verifier' in the surface contract documents only the first.
- F-6-6 [unnamed/P2] The committed code-opencode benchmark `targetSkill.root` carries a stale worktree absolute path (`/Users/.../0030-018-rust/...`) from a prior iteration, so the archived evidence depends on a machine + worktree path that no longer exists in the current tree — confirms F-4-5 and extends it to a benchmark report that is the canonical router-mode artifact for the surface.
- F-6-7 [sk-code-align/P1] code-opencode has a populated leaf-manifest at `.opencode/skills/sk-code/leaf-manifest.json:4-71` (67 leaves under workflowMode=code-opencode) but the surface RESOURCE_MAP paths inside code-opencode/SKILL.md are not packet-qualified — the typed-pair derivation must strip and re-prefix them, with no test asserting the prefixing matches `registryPacketRoots`.
- F-7-1 [playbooks/P0] A Lane C scenario can load with only id yet carry no routing gold, because the frozen loader admits any of id, expected_intent, or expected_resources while the standard validator does not require the latter fields.
- F-7-2 [playbooks/P1] The documented root-playbook validation bypasses the dedicated playbook contract by forcing generic reference validation.
- F-7-3 [catalogs/P2] The catalog snippet template says only Automated test and Manual playbook are valid test types, while the validator accepts twelve canonical types.
- F-7-4 [benchmark/P0] Compiled-routing parity evidence must be rendered from report JSON because skill-benchmark-report.md has no authoring template and is renderer-owned.
- F-9-1 [catalogs/P0] The hub catalog entry must change from opt-in/default-off wording to default-compiled plus explicit kill-switch wording in the same P4 stage as that hub's directive.
- F-9-2 [catalogs/P1] An isolated compiled-routing leaf is invalid because the catalog contract requires a canonical root inventory with one linked root entry per per-feature file.
- F-9-3 [catalogs/P1] The existing advisor_recommend feature entry omits the optional compiledRoute response field and its exact flag, allowlist, sentinel, and failure conditions.
- F-9-4 [unnamed/P1] The per-feature template claims feature-catalog trigger_phrases drive advisor routing, but the live doc-frontmatter harvester scans only references and assets markdown.
- F-9-5 [sk-doc-templates/P1] The compiled-routing leaf must describe operator-visible behavior, stable implementation anchors, automated tests, and manual-playbook links while keeping scenario execution detail outside the catalog.
- F-11-1 [playbooks/P0] The live playbook executor never explicitly enables SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING for its child process, so a LUNA run cannot deterministically exercise the compiled path.
- F-11-2 [playbooks/P0] Live Lane C scores the model's declared routing JSON and observed skill calls, not a compiled-router decision, so LUNA agreement cannot prove compiled serving.
- F-11-3 [benchmark/P1] LUNA High selection is process-wide environment configuration rather than per-scenario data, while --executor selects only the Codex versus OpenCode transport.
- F-11-4 [archiving/P1] Lane C writes its JSON and rendered Markdown only under the caller-provided outputs directory, so durable LUNA evidence requires an explicit hub benchmark path.
