.opencode/commands/speckit/resume.md:4:allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob, Task, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_search, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_match_triggers, mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_list, mcp__mk_spec_memory__session_bootstrap, mk_goal_status
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:40:Claude hooks covered only one runtime family. Other runtimes depended on the AI remembering to prime itself. Added MCP first-call priming, `session_resume`, `session_health`, and `session_bootstrap` so non-hook runtimes recover with a single main path. The OpenCode transport layer and repo-local Copilot startup wrapper extend recovery beyond hook-based runtimes.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:48:#### Stop-hook tracking and best-effort auto-save
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:50:The system had no reliable way to capture end-of-session state automatically. Stop-hook tracking parses transcript usage data, stores metrics, estimates token spend, and can trigger a best-effort `generate-context.js` save when configured thresholds are met.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:55:Runtime instructions, context-prime agents, and bootstrap surfaces drifted apart across runtimes. Standardized non-hook recovery around explicit expected behaviors: ready/stale/missing structural state, main `session_bootstrap` path, and mirrored routing/recovery tables across all runtime-facing docs.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:103:The skill advisor had no routing for the new 5-dimension capabilities, and the root README was missing the agent-improver entries. Phase 011 added 28 routing entries to the skill advisor, bumped the skill version to 1.0.0.0, and added Agent-Improver to the root README's Agent Network and Skills Library sections. Skill count updated from 19 to 20.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:116:| `mcp-server/hooks/claude/session-stop.ts` | Stop-hook token tracking and best-effort save |
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:122:| `mcp-server/handlers/session-bootstrap.ts` | Canonical hookless bootstrap surface + output schema |
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:38:The `memory` command group provides operations for the Spec Kit Memory MCP system. These 4 commands cover context preservation, unified knowledge retrieval and analysis, constitutional memory management, and database maintenance plus async ingest. Session recovery now lives under `/speckit:resume`.
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:136:/speckit:resume
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:139:/speckit:resume :auto
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:235:| 1 | `memory_context` | L1 | `/memory:search` |
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:273:| 39 | `session_bootstrap` | L1 | `/speckit:resume` |
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:291:| `/speckit:resume` | 1 | uses search/manage tools | L1 |
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:304:**Q: What is the difference between `/memory:search` and `/speckit:resume`?**
.opencode/commands/memory/README.txt:306:`/memory:search` retrieves and searches indexed knowledge using a query or subcommand. `/speckit:resume` handles session continuation and interrupted-session recovery: it reconstructs packet context from `handover.md`, then `_memory.continuity`, then canonical spec docs before deeper memory tools engage. Use `search` for knowledge lookup and `resume` when you need to continue prior work.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.6.0.0.md:153:The skill advisor keeps its working files at the repo root, out of your spec folders. When it ran from inside a packet, its workspace resolver could fall back to that packet and drop a stray `.advisor-state` directory into it. The resolver now refuses to land inside a `specs/` subtree, so the advisor writes its state where it belongs and your spec folders stay clean. A regression test pins the new behavior, and the directories that had already leaked were cleaned up.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.5.0.4.md:19:| **Orphan-sweep activation** | The Stop hook can now reap ownerless MCP daemons via the orphan-only sweeper when no session pid is available, flag-gated and default-off, never guessing the session pid. |
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.5.0.4.md:55:The Stop hook's session-cleanup no-ops without a session pid, and it deliberately refuses to guess one. When enabled, its no-session-pid branch now delegates to the orphan-only sweeper, which reaps only ownerless processes and so can never touch a live session. It ships default-off with a dry-run ramp.
