.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md:2:title: "Unified context retrieval (memory_context)"
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md:6:  - "memory_context"
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md:13:# Unified context retrieval (memory_context)
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md:29:You send a query or prompt. The system figures out what you need. That is the core idea behind `memory_context`: an L1 orchestration layer that auto-detects your task intent and routes to the best retrieval strategy without you having to pick one.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md:45:When `includeTrace` is enabled, `memory_context` also computes a trace-only `sessionTransition` payload and forwards it through the internal `memory_search` path. The contract is `trace.sessionTransition = { previousState, currentState, confidence, signalSources, reason? }`. Cold starts use `previousState: null`, the payload is omitted when trace is disabled, and this inference does not change retrieval routing beyond the existing mode-selection path. Intent telemetry consumed from the query-intent classifier now carries `classificationKind` on both `taskIntent` and `backendRouting` envelopes plus a stable `paraphraseGroup` token used so paraphrased queries map to the same group.
