.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v2+/v2.2.24.0.md:39:There was a reliability problem around Extended telemetry shipped. Extended telemetry shipped: retrieval now captures latency, mode, fallback, and quality-proxy dimensions across memory_search and memory_context. This matters because it reduces confusing failures and makes the system more dependable.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/discovery/session-health-shared-payload.md:21:The endpoint is intentionally cheaper than `session_bootstrap`. Operators run it before deeper context recovery to confirm the startup channel is alive, then escalate to `session_bootstrap` only if the health response names a recovery action.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/discovery/session-health-shared-payload.md:31:- `recovery`: named follow-on (`session_bootstrap`, manual spec walk, or no-op when ready)
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.2.1.0.md:1:This release expands System Spec Kit in three directions at once: packet-local nested changelog generation is now a shipped workflow, the `session_bootstrap` recovery expected behavior and structural safeguards were remediated after review, and the deep-research/deep-review command surfaces now sit on executable parity-tested expected behaviors. It also records the approved Codex command-discoverability direction from Packet 039 without overstating that packet as a downstream quick-reference implementation. The goal is to make the workflow easier to trust in everyday use.
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.2.1.0.md:31:#### `session_bootstrap` and `nextActions`
.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.2.1.0.md:33:The public `session_bootstrap` expected behavior already described recommended next actions, but the handler did not return a real `nextActions` payload. The docs and the implementation were telling slightly different truths. `session_bootstrap` now generates real `nextActions`, and the tool schema documents the full output shape explicitly. The recovery surface no longer depends on readers inferring behavior from docs that the handler itself did not fulfill.
